Elevated levels of α-fetoprotein and acetylcholinesterase in amniotic fluid are suggestive of neural tube defects, such as anencephaly or spina bifida. Increased amniotic fluid volume is also associated with neural tube defects. Among the options, anencephaly is a condition characterized by the absence of a major portion of the brain, and this would fit with the high α-fetoprotein levels.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The elevated α-fetoprotein and acetylcholinesterase levels, as well as the increased amniotic fluid volume, suggest an open neural tube defect. Among the options, the most severe form is anencephaly, which is the absence of a major portion of the brain, skull, and scalp. Holoprosencephaly is a less severe defect in which the brain does not divide into two hemispheres. Lissencephaly is a rare brain malformation characterized by a lack of folds in the cerebral cortex. Myelomeningocele is a type of spina bifida in which the spinal cord and its covering push through a gap in the vertebrae into a fluid-filled sac.

Holoprosencephaly is characterized by incomplete separation of the forebrain into two hemispheres, lissencephaly is characterized by a smooth brain surface and myelomeningocele is a type of spina bifida.
